segments.text: July 1978, Austin, Texas.
Interview with General Charles Bond.
This is a test.
Terry Anderson.
This is an interview with Major General Charles Bond, Jr. Today is the 21st of July, 1981.
Let's start off by talking about your early years and could you tell me about your parents?
Well, my early years with respect to the military I often thought probably started in 1930 when I went to Forrest High School in Dallas, Texas and joined the high school ROTC as a buck private.
That's the first time I put on anything resembling a military uniform and I think that's when it started.
I grew to like
the military and being a poor boy.
Tell me about that.
I want to find out about your growing up.
Tell me, where'd you grow up?
I was born in Dallas, Texas in 1915, 22nd of April.
I lived in Dallas my entire life except for the time when I entered the military service.
And then when I retired, I came back and retired in Dallas.
I had two sisters and three brothers.
Large family.
Large family.
And my father was a painter and paper painter.
We were definitely a poor family even in those days.
I was old enough in 1929, 30, 31 to remember the Depression.
And there's no doubt those times definitely made an impression on me.
Okay, we're going to talk about that a little bit later.
Let's talk about your father's education.
My father probably never went further than the fourth or fifth grade in grammar school.
He, in effect, ran away from home about the age of eight.
Really?
Yeah.
Where was he from?
Where was his home?
He was born in Dallas.
And back in the 1870s, something like that, he died at 89 years old.
And I think he went up to Colorado as a young boy.
He eventually came back home a member of a large family and started a painting business.
My mother
How successful was the painting business?
He stayed busy, but it had its ups and downs.
Of course, during the Depression, it was hard to get work.
I remember going out with him when I was a little kid to hunt rabbits to get food.
I remember cutting wood to bring home to have heat.
Indeed, I remember the Depression.
My mother, I doubt seriously if she ever finished third or fourth grade.
She was from Oklahoma.
And neither one of them had an education.
It was my young years in life that I learned the value of education and the effects of poverty.
And I guess... Who told you this, or who taught you this?
My experience.
My experience.

taught me this and I guess it was then in my younger years that I practically made a solid vow to myself that I would get an education some way and pull myself up above the poverty that my family had to live in.
I don't criticize or blame my mother and father one bit.
Matter of fact, my mother was a saint if there ever was one.
by nature of their lack of education.
In effect, they taught me negatively if you will.
They didn't know any better.
And I learned by what they didn't know and saw the impact it had on me and the family by them not being educated and so forth.
What kind of person was your dad?
My dad was a very independent
type of person, very sensitive.
He was a typical person that without an education and being poverty stricken he had an inferiority complex and at times was a very angry and almost a mean man.
Mean toward you or toward other people?
Toward the family.
I think my dad was probably responsible for taking most of the kids out of the school.
My brothers and sisters, except for one brother, never finished grammar school.
No kidding.
And then I'll get back to the A&M in a minute to how I got to A&M.
When I graduated from high school, I couldn't afford to go to college.
I had to go to work.
Did he want to take you out of high school?
He did.
Why did you ever stay in?
by just sheer determination and my friends, parents helping me, knowing I was determined to go to school.
And that's one reason I love the military, I guess.
It's my first attraction to the military.
Military wears uniform.
This makes people look equal.
Had I been a civilian, I dare say I wouldn't have been able to clothe myself properly to go to school.
During the summer, I worked.
with my dad in the painting business and save enough money to buy clothes to go to school the following fall.
What about the type of person that your mother was?
My mother was a very uneducated person, but dedicated and like I say, a perfect saint.
The deprivation she went through and the sacrifice she went through for the family was just, there's nothing in my
experience in 66 years and compared to it as far as I'm concerned.
There's no doubt that she's in heaven.
Both of them, I think, really are in heaven.
A very understanding person, and the sacrifices she made for the kids, it was something.
Now, you became a leader, and were either of your parents in any way leaders?
Definitely not.
Definitely not.
Again, that's the reason I say the things I learned from them in a negative sort of way that they weren't.

I just knew that I was going to have to learn these things or raise myself above the various levels of living that no money, no participation in social life, no clothing, actually hungry at times, respect from your fellow man.
Sure.
These things, which we didn't have, I guess was imbued in me as a kid.
And like psychiatrists and psychologists say, the things that you grow up in your environment as a kid, they affect your later life.
Sure, absolutely.
Again, I don't criticize my mother and father, nor my sisters and brothers.
Was the family in any way religious?
My mother was very religious, and she tried to continue to get kids to go to
church.
My father cared less.
My father and mother were a little bit different.
Both of them, my mother had very high morals and my father not quite so high morally.
But they stuck together.
What type of church?
The Congregation Church, First Congregation Church in Dallas, way back in the early 20s.
and then finally the Presbyterian Church.
Was religion in any way an influence on your life growing up?
Very little, very little.
Now, what were the values that they tried to teach you, or did they ever try to teach any values?
Say again?
The type of values that they tried to instill in you.
Well, my father
just told me to work.
You need to work and contribute.
And in his reasoning, he had to do this, see, when he was a kid.
Sure.
And he felt that if he had to work and contribute to the family, then so should his boys do the same thing.
And quite often, we'd work all week, and it'd end up he wouldn't pay us.
Really?
Which caused a considerable distaste between, and downright hatred sometimes.
Why wouldn't he pay you?

Well, for one thing, there were bills that you had to pay, and on the other hand, there were a lot of times, I'm sure, that Dad just felt that when he worked for the family, they had to contribute to their upkeep, and that we kids should do the same way.
Sure.
But many times he did pay us, and that's how I got money for the coming year to go to school.
So hard work.
hard work.
My dad believed in hard work, and bless his heart, he worked hard.
He was painting and climbing up and down ladders when he was in his early 80s.
And I noticed that my people called me a workaholic.
I don't consider it work.
Today I'm retired and I love to work in the yard, and people say I'm working all the time.
They call it work.
I call it diversion.
and keeping busy and loving it.
Yeah, enjoying yourself.
Enjoying it.
You became a major general leader.
In what way do you think your parents are responsible for your success?
Well, going back to my previous statement, the negative way in which they impressed me on things to achieve, to get someplace,
It might very well be one of the reasons I decided to join the United States Army.
Fifteenth Field Artillery at Fort Sam Houston in 1935 was by determination to get a chance to go to college.
I graduated from high school in 1933, Forest High School.
And I had aspirations of wanting to be an aeronautical engineer, and I knew I'd have
college to get a degree.
I wanted to go to A&M then, in the early 30s.
Well, 30s, I mean 34, I wanted to go to A&M, but I couldn't afford it.
And of course, there was a negative attitude on the part of my father.
He wanted me to work.
I did work in the station for a while, then with him for a while.
But I lost your train of thought.
What did you ask me?
I was wondering about the ways in which your parents are responsible for getting them in
Your success?
Well, again, determination.
I was going to achieve this.
This was the last thing I did.
I was going to get someplace.
This was the last thing I did.
I was going to get out of the environment.
Perhaps that's one reason I decided to join the Army.
I was going to get an education.
They didn't have one.
My older brothers and sisters didn't have an education.
Looking back now, I don't know how in the world at that age
I even had enough foresight to sit and consider such things that you might say adults consider today, what effect it's going to have on me in the future.
And I had a chance to join the Army for one year to compete for entry to West Point through
appointments that the Army gave from enlisted people.

And I went to Fort Sam Houston for one year, and I remember making a grade of 96 on the entrance exam to West Point, which would be easily qualifying me for an entry if it had a congressional appointment, but I didn't have enough there again.
I didn't have enough
clout or contacts, if you will, through my father and mother and my friends to get a congressional appointment.
But there were only 23, I think, 23 vacancies, 26, something like that.
And so you didn't go?
I didn't go.
But again, it might be that it was for the best, because I turned right around and took the written examination to the flying cadets.
And lo and behold, passed that.
So I entered the Flying Cadets without any college whatsoever in 1938.
But it seems to me, then, that one of the things that you had was a desire to escape.
Right.
Exactly.
Determination to escape, I guess I should say.
And get out of the environment.
I didn't like it.
Even at that age, I guess I was ashamed of part of it, the way we lived.
I can look back now and remember embarrassing moments that I was ashamed of.
No different, I guess, from any poverty-stricken family.
Hunger never did really bother me.
I say I went hungry, I didn't really go real hungry, but definitely without money.
I went to high school many days without a penny in my pocket and skipped lunch.
How'd you get along with your brothers and sisters?
You had a large crew.
My brothers and sisters respected me then, and of course they respect me today.
As a matter of fact, my youngest brother, through my efforts, went to Texas A&M.
I paid his way through.
And then he followed me and went to the Air Force and did fairly well.
He got to be a lieutenant colonel before he retired.
My oldest brother
God bless his heart, helped me.
He bought my graduation suit when I graduated from high school.
No kidding.
My oldest sister, who's dead now, was, again, she was like my mother, quite a saint.
And she helped me.
She knew that I wanted to improve.
And she had the same ideas and philosophies of life I had.
But another sister I had, we didn't get along too well together.
and another younger brother, we had respect, mutual respect for each other.
My childhood life definitely had an impact on my desires to become something in life.
And I attribute that, as I say, to sort of a negative way to my mother and father.
What they didn't have, I would determine and get.
Okay, now let's talk about your education.
But before we do that, I want to check.
I wear a hearing aid, but it's not really that bad.
Mostly it's resolution.
Okay, now as far as your education, let's start...
It's rather unusual when a father does not finish high school or even go to high school and then does not want their son to go on.
And you did.
And your other brothers didn't.
You must have been very determined.
So let's talk about your education, your early years.
Well, of course, I went to grammar school at Colonial Hill Grammar School in South Dallas, near where we lived.
And always did well.
Again, I guess I did very well in grammar school.
As a matter of fact, I was better than a C average kid, I'm sure.
And I did well in athletics.
I was a member of the softball team.
And got along well with students.
Always got along well with other students.
Made a U one day.
one time in music, and it almost killed me.
And I remember crying and talking to the teacher about it, and the next grade, which was three months after that, I practiced straight A's.
And this carried on through high school.
In high school I practiced straight A's.
What were your favorite subjects?
I think in grammar school, my favorite subjects were drawing and arithmetic.
In high school, definitely science, physics, and military.
I loved the ROTC.
And it was obvious as I proceeded through high school that I was doing well, or better than the average, and I felt more competent.
And I guess it's one of the reasons
Self-confidence, you know, you develop.
Yeah, school developed some self-confidence for you because you were doing so well in comparison with your peers.
Is that right?
Right.
OK, were you in activities?
You said earlier that you played some softball.
Were you on the varsity in any sports?
Well, in grammar school, I was always on the soccer team, the softball team.
I was one of the dominant figures in my classes in all
sports in a grammar school, if you will, like soccer and softball.
In high school, I was on the field and track team as a discus and javelin thrower, and I represented Forest High School.
some medals.
When I went to summer military camp, I always won those events in the entire summer camp of Walter Dulles High School, in the discus and javelin, and in the baseball throw.
I probably still hold the record for baseball throw at Camp Dulles at Mineral Wells in 1934.
No kidding.
As a kid that age throwing a baseball is 320 feet.
That's fantastic.
I'm sure that record shows.
You threw a baseball on a football field?
320 feet.
And even when it hit, it hit a flagpole about 20 feet above the ground.
So it had gone further.
And furthermore, it was a wet baseball.
And football, I was a- You should have played in the outfield.
You should have played in the outfield.
Well, I played usually second base.
And the other sport in high school was football.
I didn't care for basketball or baseball.
I actually didn't have time much going for those sports.
But I was a famous one minute man in football.
They put me in at the last minute if they knew they had completely lost or they knew they had won.
I was a halfback.
I loved football.
Today I love it.
How good were you?
I was a member of the second team.
But at that time, there was no doubt.
Matter of fact, I became the cadet colonel in my senior year to command the regiment of Forest High School.
OK, let's talk about that.
And that took most of my time.
And furthermore, I was vice president of my senior class and a member of tall beta pi for the National Honor Society for high grades and all.
But really, I was quite active.
And I really didn't have much time to devote
to football, I think I could have done better.
But my coach, who was also my algebra coach, knew of my other activity.
And I think it was just sort of a compromise.
But I was good enough to make the second team.
I'm always interested in when generals started leadership roles.
And it appears to me that you started yours by the time you were 14, 15 years old.
Is that true?
Or would you tell me?

I would imagine that, since you asked me the question and being objective and honest about it, I would say that in about the middle of my high school career, my teachers, and particularly my commandant, Colonel Coleman of Forrest High School in Dallas, began to recognize
above average devotion to military and to really anything I did.
I was an A student and anything I did I always strived to do it the best I could.
That was a motto that I developed as a kid and still have.
If you don't do it right, don't do it at all.
I teach my kids the same thing.
I guess they saw it and began to promote me faster.
I was promoted faster than my cohorts of compatriots and military, and I rapidly became the, well, I was made the top man in the high school ROTC, the cadet colonel.
And I'm sure it was in those last few years in high school that

to my staying in the military and even went beyond that to get a little bit more money and at the behest of some of my older friends in high school ROTC who were members of the Texas National Guard, I joined the 144th Infantry in Dallas as a private in an infantry outfit and rapidly became a platoon sergeant in the Texas National Guard in the infantry.
How old were you at that time?
I was a junior in high school in 1932, so that made me 17 years old.
So when you were 18 you were already a sergeant in the National Guard?
Yes.
When I was 17 I was a sergeant in the Texas National Guard infantry and I was the cadet colonel of the Forest High School ROTC Regiment.
And I think it was there that really I still wanted an aeronautical engineer degree and to build airplanes.
And I think it was after a high school ROTC that I had a chance to join the Army for one year to get to West Point, and that was a way to get my education.
Not doing that, then joining the flying cadets and becoming actually a military pilot in the Army Air Corps at that time.
Then I really decided to stick to the military and be a fighter pilot.
What was it about the military that was so attractive to you when you were 17 years old?
Well, it partly solved my problem of feeling on a level with my
fellow students, both girls and boys, wore uniforms.
And therefore, I wasn't, I didn't appear in class in some second grade types of clothes, if you will.
And that increased my, helped increase my ego.
And my closest friend, whose parents were Bohemians,
They took an interest in me and recognized my desire to be a higher-class person and all, and they actually paid for my summer camp.
They bought my first pair of boots when I became an officer in high school ROTC.
Actually, high-grade German-made boots in Germany when they visited Europe, they bought me a pair of German boots, German-made field boots back.
I wore those all year during my four years in high school.
I probably had them half sold at least six times.
So one of the things you liked about the military was that everybody in uniform was on an equal point.
Right.
And I liked the, I won't say I liked the regimentation, but I liked the feeling of being a part of something.
As I became a corporal or sergeant, I developed the feel of commanding people, or if you will, not so much commanding them, but motivating them.
Having a person do something that I told him to do.
Follow orders.
Follow orders.
I learned the difference between people.
very rapidly in telling a person to do something.
When he wouldn't do it, when he would do it, when you're not sure he's going to do it, the dependability of people.
I began to learn how to motivate people to do things that they didn't want to do.
I learned to recognize the differences in young men's feelings, whether they wanted to be in the military or not.
There were many wealthy children, children from wealthy parents that went to my high school.
And there were a lot of poor boys that went to my high school, but the majority of them were wealthy people from Jewish families in the South Dallas area.
And many of these boys would be under me in military, and here I was, a poor boy.
What about the discipline?
Did you like discipline?
I didn't mind discipline.
As a matter of fact, you can tell by what I've told you so far that I learned to discipline myself.
I'm a self-disciplined person, very, very self-disciplined person.
And I have no patience with a person who isn't self-disciplined.
This is a characteristic I developed.
Well, see, this fits with military.
I don't mind discipline.
I admire it.
I love confidence, competence, reliability.
I am happy to see the results of my work.
I'm happy to see my impact on people.
I take pride in this.
I take great pride in
getting a person to do something, and while he's doing it, he likes it.
I learned this in military.
In other words, it was the first real big step in overcoming my poor environment as a poor kid.
I began to rise above it, and I loved it.

And it was shortly after my graduation from high school in ROTC and being a member of the National Guard, which continued on for two or three years until I entered the flying contest in 1938, that I knew I was going to stay with the military.
So you had already made up your mind as a young man that you wanted to have a military career?
I had made up my mind in my latter teenage years that I was going to have a military career.
Did you consider yourself popular in high school?
It's interesting you ask that question.
I was elected the most popular student in my senior class band.
And surprisingly, the girl I was going with was elected the most popular girl.
And the way they put it, though, is the one most likely to succeed and best liked by his fellow students.
the way they described it.
And I'll never forget it as long as I live.
And I'm impressed with what you're doing on the team.
My picture was published in the front page of Dallas Morning News that day.
I bet you have a copy of that around the house someplace.
I have a picture in one of my albums someplace.
Now, it seems to me then that when you graduated from high school, you had some firm goals.
Is that true?
Yes, when I graduated from high school, I definitely wanted college education, and I wanted to go to Texas A&M.
That was in 1933.
But the influence of my father again, the pressure, if you will, to work, and the fact that he couldn't or wouldn't help
And he really couldn't help financially to send me to college, because they had other kids to take care of, too.
I just knew I was going to have to work for a while.
And it was in... Did you ever think about applying for scholarships to any universities?
I really didn't have anything to establish the basis for a scholarship, except good grades.
I didn't do it.
I think it might have been because
I figured I was going to have to work a while to help the family.
Why did you think that you wanted to go to Texas A&M instead of some other university?
Well, Texas A&M was one thing, was military school.
Sure.
And I couldn't get a congressional appointment to go to West Point.
Yeah.
And at least I'd be able to take military, and I just liked what I had learned about
colleges compared to all of them, but I just want to go to Texas A&M.
It's a band school.
You just liked what you heard about it.
Right, right.
Now, let's talk about the Depression.
You said that the Depression had an impact on your life.
Would you explain that?
Well, when you live in a crowded house, and sometimes all you have at night is

lot of beans and if you get in late the other kids have eaten more than their share and not much left and when you have to sleep in a bed with as a young kid now this was in 1929 let's say I was 14 years old maybe have to sleep in even in the same bed with your sister in a bedroom with

two other beds with some other kids in it, and having an outside toilet, no indoor sewage facilities, and in a kitchen where my mother had no modern sink to work out of, had to carry water from outside, and having to go out and chop wood to put in the stove for heat and for cooking.
and sometimes it seemed that I was the only boy to do it.

Having the lights turned off because you can't pay the bill, having the phone cut up because you can't pay the bill, not being able to pay the doctor bills, seeing my sisters and brothers go with teeth that needed
fixing and seeing my fellow students having their teeth fixed and my sister's brother's not.
All of these things make an impression on me.
What was that impression?
You want to do better.
You want to get out of it.
You know you can do better.
Detecting a

feeling from my relatives, who were better off than my mother and father on both sides, particularly my father's side, where they looked down on my family, even my, looked down even on my father, his own brother and sister did.
These things left an imprint on me.
I guess all of these things made me quite an analytical type of a person, even in my young teens.
into why these, why this, why so forth and so forth, and having to submit and work while my fellow students played and had money to go to shows and so forth, not being

able to dress well enough to even have dates really living a little bit in chain all of these things have an impact and there are all of these things all the economic conditions did you say that your father
had a hard time finding work during the Depression?
So it got worse during the Depression?
Yes.
Oh, yes.
You said 1929, of course, that's when the Depression starts, but it really hits the balls in 1932.
Well, 32 and 33, that's right.
And it was in 1929, 1933, you see that I was in high school.
And like I say, I had my
friends, parents, not provided the money to buy my uniform, particularly those boots, costly boots, a uniform which you wore every day to go to high school.
I am sure, I'm almost sure, I had to drop out of high school because I wouldn't have clothes to wear.
My dad didn't have enough money to, sometimes you've got to work for a week or so.
And living from day to day,

He wouldn't give me, some mornings even, you know, upset, my dad wouldn't even give me the fifteen cents for lunch money that I would use to buy, you know, maybe a hamburger and a glass of milk for lunch.
Sometimes he's irate at me because I wouldn't quit school.
He wouldn't give me the fifteen cents.
But nevertheless, somehow or another, I always managed to have seven cents
14 cents, 7 cents to come back on car fare in my last year in high school.
Many people were poverty stricken in our environment where we lived during the Depression.
But it seemed like we were always worse off.
My dad was not a good manager.
He was a selfish person, and he'd spend money on his car before he'd spend money on some of us kids.
What did your mother think about it?
My mother and father thought an awful lot about this.
Her philosophy was, I guess I got my basic philosophy from my mother, sacrifice and so forth.
But she and my father clashed an awful lot.
And of course, the environment is what made it that way, not enough to go around.
And my mother probably didn't get along well at all.
And of course, it's another thing I observed.
Sure.
Did your father ever accept, or did your family ever accept any federal help?
Because this is the time that Franklin Roosevelt comes in and establishes the New Deal.
My father definitely would take any handout he could get and wasn't ashamed of it at all.
And so he accepted federal funds?
Yes.
Well, I don't remember any particular federal funds at that time, like food stamps as they are today.
But it seemed like there was some sort of an organization where he actually went down and got food.
I can't remember this very well.
But I do need church or some YMCA or Salvation Army or something.
No, we never got any help from that.
Through my mother's religious zeal to keep us kids in church, the minister would come to see us, but I don't remember ever any financial help from a church or any YMCA organization.
My neighbors would help, yes.
My relatives, particularly my favorite Uncle John, dad's brother, who was a court reporter at that time, he would help a lot.
And I became the pride and joy of his life when I graduated from high school with honors.
It was hard, hard times.
Did your father ever work for the WPA or the CCCs or anything like that?
No, no.
And to carry on and answer your question, I remember it was in 1936 and 37, through the Home Owners Loan Corporation, where they helped people pay for their home.
My dad, through a job he had with a southwestern life insurance company man, painting houses,
buy a house in Oak Cliff at quite a reduced price.
And immediately thereafter, it was obvious he couldn't make the payments.
The payments were $37 and $50.
No, the payments were $50 a month.
And I remember taking a job with the US Treasury dispersing office in 1938.
six, and seven.
And I would pay those payments on that home.
That's the only way we could keep that home.
You made that much money?
I made $37.50 every two weeks.
And I would take $25 each two weeks and keep up the payments on that.
Whenever he failed, I would make the payments.
That's the only way we kept that home for a while.
How long did you keep that home?
We kept that home until I...

left went to the flying cadets and uh was away from home of course and military and then my dad lost it he could no longer make those payments what what political party did he vote for i guess my dad today painted grave was still a democrat uh did he support franklin roosevelt i he
He talked openly about supporting the president, but I doubt, seriously, my dad and mother ever voted in their entire life.
But he was definitely a Democrat.
Hated the Republicans.
To him, the Republican was a rich man's party.
The Democrat was a poor man's party.
Therefore, I'm a Democrat.
Did that have any influence on your political philosophy?
Looking back, no.
Today, I'd call myself, really,
if you will, more of an independent, I've always thought for myself.

Of course, in the military life, you know, it's a little bit different, but I'd call myself more of an independent, definitely, absolutely, and absolutely a conservative, assuming the conservative and the old, you know, definition.
A conservative on what issues?
Every issue you can think of.

I think that the Social Security Act, although conceived probably in the right spirit at the time of the Roosevelt administration, is probably today one of the worst things that could have happened to this country from the standpoint of our democratic system and the old system in the United States, the economy where a man has a chance to work.
make a living.
I think it's, I think in concept, it is a horrible thing.
And I'm drawing it.
And you're drawing it.
And I'm drawing it.
Do you see any inconsistency there?
Nope.
I paid them.
Okay.
You did.
Right.
And I wonder what's going to happen to

The money that you're putting in this thing now, and your later life, the main thing that I don't like about is they tell me right now, we're getting off subject, but this is something I feel strong about.
Right now, I cannot make more than $463 a month, or they'll take money away from me.
Now, that is something.
Where's the incentive?
Where's the incentive?
They say when you get 72, you make all the money you want to.
It's basically wrong, the concept of it.
To pay, well, in effect, if you will, you can do it paying people not to work.
And no wonder there is graft in it.
No wonder it opens the field for
People who don't have the so-called people of the minority, if you will, and the culture of some of them.
No wonder.
Well, we're all going to get back now.
I wanted to know your political philosophy.
And basically, you say you're conservative as far as everything's concerned.
Well, I am for it.
